I am of the mind that whether an act has a given legal effect is
determined at the time that act takes place, according to the Rules in
force at that time.  Rule 101 says as much.  I interpret Rule 108 to
say that no Rule Change has effect prior to its effectuation; that is,
the adoption of a Rule Change has no effect on the law, and therefore
the legal effect of any act, prior to its adoption.  (I'm not sure
that Rule 108's retroactivity clause actually adds anything to Rule
101; discussion on this point welcome.)  

I do NOT believe that Rule 108 would prohibit a Rule that operates so
as to cancel, reverse, or modify the legal effect of an act which
occurred prior to that Rule's enactment (or amendment), but I believe
that, generally, such operation must be explicitly specified (the
default is to let prior legal effects stand).

Applying this general theory to the situation of casting Votes, I
analyze the problem as follows: The act is that of transmitting a
message to the Assessor which purports to contain Votes.  The legal
effect of this act is determined in light of the attendant
circumstances which are extant at the moment the message is
transmitted.  In order to determine whether a purported Vote is
legally cast by that message, the Assessor (and, subsequently, if
called upon to do so, a Judge) must examine (among other factors)
whether the message was sent during the designated Voting Period of
that Proposal.  I would argue that the Voting Period of a Proposal is
computed _de novo_ every time a Voting Message is sent, according to
the law then extant, not once when the Proposal is distributed.

Exploring this conclusion, we see that extending the Voting Period
generically may cause the Voting Period of prior Proposals to be
reopened.  Does this create a problem?  Yes, but not a deadly one.

Suppose that we amended Rule 693 to state that the Voting Period of
all Proposals is 10 years, beginning at the time the Proposal was
distributed.  Under the theory that I have now espoused, this would
mean that every Proposal ever made in Agora would be again open for
Voting.  However, the prior determinations that these Proposals had
been adopted (for those that were adopted) would have been legal
because they were legally adopted under the law then in force; thus,
there would be no need for (and in fact no legal justification for)
recission of those results.  This could lead to the curious result of
a single Proposal being adopted twice (or in fact many times, given
multiple extensions of the voting period).  I am not particularly
bothered by this; it might be messy, and horribly inconvenient (not to
mention running into all sorts of recordkeeping problems), but I see
no legal inconsistency at all.

Suppose that, instead, we shorten the Voting Period from its present
value of seven days to six hours.  This would, of course, have no
effect on those Proposals which were distributed more than seven days
previously; the change would have no effect on the legal ability of
anyone to cast Votes on those Proposals.  (It might, however, create a
rather difficult situation for the Assessor; he would have a very
limited amount of time to report the results of those Proposals
without violating ASAP requirements, since the rule change would push
back the moment that triggered the ASAP duty by 6.5 days.)  Proposals
distributed more than six hours prior, but less than seven days prior,
would have their effective voting periods chopped off at the moment
of adoption.

The situation discussed in CFJ 944 is yet another odd one; in this
case Proposals distributed during a given time period had no statutory
Voting Period at all, making it impossible to cast a legal vote upon
those Proposals for a portion of the period which later became the
statutory Voting Period of those Proposals.  In this case, the
effective voting period was truncated at the front end, instead of the
rear.  Consider also the effect on existing Proposals of amending Rule
693 to state that the Voting Period of a Proposal begins seven days
after that Proposal is distributed.  

Effective voting period (the actual period during which one can
legally cast a vote upon a given Proposal) need not equal statutory
voting period, which I believe is the crux of the issue here.  I
believe I have demonstrated that the effective voting period of a
Proposal can be of nearly any length, and need not even be a single
contiguous interval of time.  While this theory can lead to messy and
sometimes unintuitive results, it does not (as far as I can tell)
engender contradiction.

Curiously, none of this has anything to do with CFJ 1111, and Steve
has no excuse but to Judge TRUE.  Proposals 3810-3812 were distributed
Mon, 30 Nov 1998 18:29:29 +1100 (EST).  CFJ 1111 was called Mon, 14
Dec 1998 11:49:26 +1100, almost 14 days later.  It is obvious that the
Rules at the time that CFJ 1111 was called designated that the Voting
Period of these Proposals ended at Mon, 7 Dec 1998 18:29:29 +1100,
which preceded the date that CFJ 1111 was called; thus, its statement
is obviously true.  


