"Steve" == Steve Gardner <gardner@silas-1.cc.monash.edu.au> writes:

Steve> Putting it another way: when talking of the Voting Periods of
Steve> P3810-3812, you say that it's what we *now* say that's
Steve> important. We *now* say that the VPs concluded at D+7. But when
Steve> talking of the votes, you say that it's what we *then* said
Steve> that's important. The votes cast after D+7 are legal because we
Steve> would have said they were legal at the time they were
Steve> cast. What justifies these different and apparently
Steve> inconsistent ways of speaking?

I don't see the inconsistency.  The real problem is that we really
don't care what the Voting Period of a Proposal is, except for the
purpose of determining whether a message purporting to contain Votes
has the effect of casting Votes (and for a few other sundry purpose,
the analysis of which is quite similar) and for determining the time
by which the Assessor is required to announce the results of Voting.

Steve> We can say, for example, that although we would have said a
Steve> vote was legal at the time it was cast, that is not what we now
Steve> say. We now say that the vote was illegal. 

This flies in the face of Rule 101.  Whether an act is legal or
illegal is determined based on the law in force at the time the act
took place, not the law which exists at any other time.  We might say
that the act in question "would be" illegal under the present law, but
"was not illegal" under the law then in force.  Saying that the act
"is" illegal is plain wrong; the subjunctive voice must be used to
indicate that the statement is a contrafactual hypothetical.

Steve> To save the D/E model, then, some answer must be given to the
Steve> question I raised above. We need some principled reason for
Steve> distinguishing between those aspects of the past whose
Steve> descriptions we may permissibly change in the present, and
Steve> those we may not.

If by "description" you mean "legal effect", and by "event" you mean
"act", my opinion is we cannot, in the present, change the description
of any past event whatsoever, but we can attach new meaning to past
events if we so elect.

