In one sense Assessor's Reports do something similar - remember that
a Proposal only takes effect, if it has been Adopted, when the Report
is sent, or if you want to pick nits, "at the time date-stamped on"
the Report.

Now, R106 says a Proposal is Adopted "if [...] it receives the
required number of votes". The Rule which defines "the required
number of votes" is R955, and it says that at the end of the VP "the
uncancelled votes which have been legally cast shall be counted by
the Assessor".

> Laurent> what matters is the legal status of Votes *at the time the
> Laurent> Assessor counts them*. 
> 
> I disagree, although I think the argument is close.  Rule 683
> states that a "Voting Entity votes ... _when_, during the Voting
> Period of that Proposal, e informs the Assessor of the vote or
> votes e is casting ...".  To me, this clearly indicates that a
> message purporting to contain Votes has the legal effect of Voting
> _at the time it is sent_.  

That is indeed clear... in all situations except those when the
Voting Period of a Proposal varies. That is precisely when, under
the view that the VP is merely the designation by the Rules of an
interval of time such that messages purporting to contain Votes and
which were sent during that period should be counted as legally cast
on the relevant Proposal, the meaning of R683 is debatable. Does that
Rule grant to such messages the status of 'legal votes' once and 
irrevocably at the time they are sent, or does it, as it were, only
come into play when the Assessor gets around to counting Votes...


