Steve Gardner wrote:
>
>I am troubled by the sense of a double standard lurking here, however.
>If we can, in the present, change the description of some moment in time
>in the past without acting retroactively, why can we not also, in the
>present, change the description of some action in the past without
>acting retroactively? 
>
>Putting it another way: when talking of the Voting Periods of
>P3810-3812, you say that it's what we *now* say that's important. We
>*now* say that the VPs concluded at D+7. But when talking of the votes,
>you say that it's what we *then* said that's important. The votes cast
>after D+7 are legal because we would have said they were legal at the
>time they were cast. What justifies these different and apparently
>inconsistent ways of speaking?

To me, it is the language of R683 and R693 themselves.  R693 says
that the voting period *is* such and such, which to me indicates
a designation.  R683 says that a player *votes* when e does such-and-such,
to me indicating an action.

You may speak of retrospectively changing the status of a vote to illegal,
but I believe that this is (partly) based on mistaking a common usage
of language for the Rules.

We may speak of an "illegal vote" and everyone knows what we mean.  But
the Rules recognize no such thing as an illegal vote.  A given action
is either voting legally, or not voting at all.  What we commonly call
an "illegal vote" is technically an attempt to vote which fails to do so.
It is not a vote at all.

Of course, then your argument simply makes a slight correction: whereas
previously you asked, "If we can retrospectively designate the voting
period, why can we not retrospectively designate the legality or
illegality of a vote?"  Now, instead, you ask "If we can retrospectively
designate the voting period, why can we not retrospectively designate
whether something is or is not a vote?"

The answer to that question lies also in R683, which states,

      Once cast, a
      vote cannot be changed or cancelled by the Voting Entity which
      cast it, although it may be cancelled as other Rules require.

We have no Rule here requiring the cancellation of a vote.

To answer the more general question, could the status of an action
as a vote or not a vote be changed without such a sentence as the
above, I would answer yes.  (This position is probably now closer to
the D/D model than to the D/E model.  Oh well.  "Do I contradict myself?
Very well then I contradict myself.  (I am large, I contain multitudes.)"
--Walt Whitman)

Anyway, you will object that this allows virtually anything to be
changed retrospectively.  This is true.  But this is no worse--and,
_de facto_, no different, than allowing virtually anything to be
"changed" via a legal fiction, something which you convinced me
was possible long ago.

That is to say, yes, it would be undesirable to say "Bob's vote on P643
is FOR, effective now," when he in fact voted AGAINST, but it is no more
or less undesirable than saying "Bob's vote on P643 shall be considered
to be FOR."  In our discussion of "considered" many moons ago, it was
you who convinced me that such a sentence would be fully effective.

Chuck


